<p>Is there a way to select an uncle of an element with css? Concretely, I am writing a GreaseMonkey script for pages which have entries of the following forms:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;ruby&gt;   &lt;span class="under"&gt;     &lt;span class="wk_K"&gt;決&lt;/span&gt;   &lt;/span&gt;   &lt;rt&gt;き&lt;/rt&gt; &lt;/ruby&gt; &lt;ruby&gt;   &lt;span class="under"&gt;決&lt;/span&gt;   &lt;rt&gt;き&lt;/rt&gt; &lt;/ruby&gt; </code></pre>  <p>I want to hide every <code>rt</code> field that appears next to a <code>wk_K</code> field (unless I hover over the latter), i.e. above the first <code>rt</code> in the example above should be hidden, but not the second one. </p>  <p>Sometimes the <code>&lt;span class="under"&gt;</code> is not there, and then the adjacent sibling selector works fine:</p>  <pre><code>ruby .wk_K + rt {visibility:hidden;} ruby .wk_K:hover + rt {visibility:visible;} </code></pre>  <p>How can I achieve the same effect when the <code>wk_K</code> field is nested in a <code>&lt;span class="under"&gt;</code>, i.e. if I want to select the 'adjacent uncle'?</p>